90 - Subsets II
Problem Statement

Given an integer array nums that may contain duplicate elements, return all possible subsets (the power set). The solution set must not contain duplicate subsets.

Approach: Backtracking + Sorting

Since the array may contain duplicate elements, we first sort the array. Sorting places duplicate values next to each other, making it easy to skip repeated subsets.

Using backtracking:

Every current combination is a valid subset, so add it to the result.
Explore all possible elements starting from the current index.
Skip duplicate elements at the same recursion level.
Backtrack after exploring each choice.
Algorithm
Sort the input array.
Start backtracking from index 0.
Add the current subset to the result.
Iterate through the remaining elements.
Skip duplicates using:
if (i > start && nums[i] == nums[i - 1])
    continue;
Include the current element in the subset.
Recurse for the next index.
Backtrack by removing the last element.
Continue until all subsets are generated.
Code
class Solution {
    public List<List<Integer>> subsetsWithDup(int[] nums) {
        List<List<Integer>> result = new ArrayList<>();

        Arrays.sort(nums);

        backtrack(0, nums, new ArrayList<>(), result);

        return result;
    }

    private void backtrack(int start,
                           int[] nums,
                           List<Integer> current,
                           List<List<Integer>> result) {

        result.add(new ArrayList<>(current));

        for (int i = start; i < nums.length; i++) {

            if (i > start && nums[i] == nums[i - 1]) {
                continue;
            }

            current.add(nums[i]);

            backtrack(i + 1, nums, current, result);

            current.remove(current.size() - 1);
        }
    }
}
Dry Run
Input
nums = [1,2,2]

After sorting:

[1,2,2]

Generated subsets:

[]
[1]
[1,2]
[1,2,2]
[2]
[2,2]

Output:

[
 [],
 [1],
 [1,2],
 [1,2,2],
 [2],
 [2,2]
]
Why Skip Duplicates?
if (i > start && nums[i] == nums[i - 1])
    continue;

This condition prevents generating the same subset multiple times.

Example:

nums = [1,2,2]

Without skipping duplicates:

[1,2]
[1,2]

could be generated more than once.

Complexity Analysis
Time Complexity
O(2^n)

Each element can either be included or excluded.

Space Complexity
O(n)

Used by the recursion stack and current subset.

Key Takeaway

The key idea is to use Backtracking to generate all subsets and Sorting to handle duplicate elements. By skipping duplicate values at the same recursion level, we ensure that every subset appears exactly once in the final result.
